To create an ASP.NET Core API proxy, you can use the `HttpClient` class to make requests to another endpoint. Here's an example of how you can do this:

**Using `HttpClient`**

```csharp
[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class ProxyController : ControllerBase
{
    private readonly IHttpClientFactory _httpClientFactory;

    public ProxyController(IHttpClientFactory httpClientFactory)
    {
        _httpClientFactory = httpClientFactory;
    }

    [HttpGet]
    public async Task<IActionResult> Get(string url)
    {
        var client = _httpClientFactory.CreateClient();
        var response = await client.GetAsync(url);

        if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
        {
            return Ok(await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync());
        }
        else
        {
            return StatusCode((int)response.StatusCode, await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync());
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `IHttpClientFactory` is used to create a new instance of `HttpClient` for each request. This is a good practice to avoid issues with `HttpClient` being static.

